        <body>       
                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>S. MORAIS&#44;<lb/>
                546 N. Fifth St.<lb/></p>
            <p>Philadelphia&#44; August 1st 1890<lb/></p>
            <p>A work in English on the administration of<lb/> justice after Talmudical dicta ought to serve<lb/> a twofold purpose.  It should show the<lb/> uninitiated the broad humanitarianism pervading<lb/> the teachings of men who lived when laws &#34;written<lb/> not in ink but in blood&#34; were in force&#44; and dispel<lb/> deep rooted but ill founded prejudices.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Reverend Dr. Samuel Mendelsohn has prepared<lb/> such a work&#44; for which familiarity with the<lb/> original sources qualified him.  The few<lb/> pages from the manuscript kindly read in my presence left upon<lb/> me the impression that the author has labored<lb/> conscientiously&#44; searching with untiring industry<lb/> with Rabbinical authorities&#44; to ensure correctness.<lb/></p>
            <p>From the little which I heard&#44; I argue<lb/> that <del>that</del> the statements made throughout<lb/> the book can claim valid support&#44; and therefore<lb/> the <del>confidence</del> credence of such as wish to learn history<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>based upon well authenticated facts.<lb/></p>
            <p>To the honesty of Talmudic quotations and to the<lb/> value of <del>his</del> literary <del>labors</del> endeavours&#44; Dr Mendelsohn<lb/> has added a feature which has specially pleased<lb/> me much.  I noticed a reverential<lb/> tone in his allusions to the custodians of<lb/> Jewish traditions&#45;&#45;the Pharisses.  So tra&#45;<lb/>&#45;duced have <del>been</del> those wise&#45;hearted Sages been by pseudo liberality and by ignorance&#59;<lb/> so <del>misrepresented</del> aspersed <del>has been</del> is still the <del>name of a</del> school<lb/> of <del>learning</del> sacred lore to which our people owes its continuance<lb/> in the face of tremendous odds&#44; that I felt refreshed<lb/> on hearing <del>their merits</del> praises richly merited.<lb/>  I think that I may commend to a <del>discrimi&#45;<lb/>nating</del> public Dr Mendelsohn&#39;s forthcoming work<lb/> to a discriminating public.<lb/>  S Morais<lb/></p>
            <p>&#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/></p>
            </body>
